The amazing Honda commercial called “Paper”! This stop-motion animated masterpiece was released in 2015 and took the advertising world by storm! The entire commercial is hand-drawn, using thousands of individual cut-out paper illustrations. These are manipulated frame-by-frame to create a mesmerizing flow of different Honda machinery coming to life, transforming, and interacting with each other. It showcases the history and breadth of Honda’s engineering, starting with their early stationary engines and moving through motorcycles, lawnmowers, outboard motors, cars, robots, and even a jet. Each scene seamlessly transitions to the next, highlighting the innovation and evolution of their technology. “Paper” was lauded for its originality, artistry, and emotional impact. It won numerous awards, including an Emmy, and was praised for its nostalgic tone and clever storytelling. Animals (bears as well) often appear confused by mirrors due to a lack of self-recognition, interpreting their reflections as another animal, which can trigger curiosity, aggression, or social responses. Only a few species demonstrate the ability to recognize themselves, indicating a higher level of cognitive ability and self-awareness. In Shanghai, teenage jump rope whiz Cen Xiaolin outdid himself! At a Double Dutch competition, he rocketed past his own record, clearing the rope a staggering 228 times in 30 seconds for the “most alternate step skips” category. This smashes his previous record of 208 set in 2016. Videos show the 17-year-old in a blur of motion, his powerful jumps earning him the nickname “world’s most powerful thighs” after dominating at the World Jump Rope Championship earlier this year. There, he even cleared 1,141 skips in 3 minutes (averaging 6.33 jumps per second!). The Shanghai contest brought together 400 rope-skipping athletes from around the globe.
